A Harvest MCP server is a third-party integration that allows AI assistants, such as Claude Desktop, to interact with Harvest time tracking and project management APIs using the Model Context Protocol [1][2][3]. By acting as a bridge, these servers enable you to perform tasks like listing time entries, managing timers, viewing project details, and generating reports via natural language prompts [2][4][5].

Multiple independent implementations exist, including packages distributed via npm and custom Python-based servers [1][2][4][3][5]. To use one, you typically configure your MCP client with the server's command and your Harvest API credentials [2][5].

Example configuration for an MCP client using an npm-based server:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "harvest": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@ianaleck/harvest-mcp-server"],
      "env": {
        "HARVEST_ACCESS_TOKEN": "your_personal_access_token",
        "HARVEST_ACCOUNT_ID": "your_account_id"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

These servers require a valid Harvest personal access token and account ID to authenticate requests to the Harvest API v2 [2][3][5].
